John Edward: Language skills are important for global citizens
Scottish private schools have remained at the forefront of academic excellence and continued to do so in 2018 with the next outstanding exam results, reinforced by personal and collective success in sports, arts, music and other community endeavors.
With more than 30,000 students across Scotland and represented by the Council of Scottish Private Schools (SCIS), these schools strive to provide the best service to their students and their parents.
Private schools aim to prepare students for further and higher education, for their chosen profession, and for their place as world citizens.
As an education sector that is able to design and implement a curriculum adapted to the circumstances, we can see that modern languages continue to be well-known and desired subjects in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, “If you talk to a man in a language he understands, it comes to his head.
If you talk to him in his language, it will reach his heart.”
This is a powerful reminder that we cannot rely solely on English if we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
From this year’s recent exam results, we can see that at the top of the tables are the languages with the highest exam completion rates among private schools.
In total, 68 percent of students who studied foreign languages achieved a high score of A.
Data collected from a total of 74 SCIS schools show that 72 percent of students received an A in Mandarin, 72 percent of German learners, 69 percent of French learners, and 63 percent of Spanish learners.
This shows that Scottish private schools support foreign languages as a vital life skill that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Languages, which are now among the subjects of choice, are included in the curricula of private schools and other schools in the same way as STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering, and mathematics).
A 2014 survey by the UK Commission for Employment and Skills revealed that 17% of respondents identified a lack of language skills as one of the reasons why employers have difficulty finding workers for vacancies.
Therefore, language skills are becoming more and more mandatory in order to prepare young people for their future jobs.
To the extent that more desirable job offers require language skills, such skills are becoming essential in a globalised world.
Regardless of the career choice made, acquiring a second language will give a person a real advantage in the future, since language skills are lifelong.
Being able to communicate directly with foreign citizens gives a multilingual person an immediate competitive advantage.
According to a 2013 YouGov survey of more than 4,000 adults in the UK, 75 percent of respondents did not speak any foreign language well enough to have a conversation about it. The only language with a two-digit percentage of proficients was French with 15 percent.
Therefore, the funding of language learning is important for today’s children at this time.
Knowledge of several languages, especially those of emerging economies, gives children a better chance of finding a good job.
Different languages are taught in every school in Scotland.
A number of schools tend to focus on classical modern languages, while other schools teach languages that are considered the most important in the UK for 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Regardless of the child’s interests, private schools always have the opportunity to choose between several languages taught by experts in their field.
Scottish private schools are committed to providing a learning environment that prepares and equips children with the skills they need to succeed, whatever the future holds for them.
It can no longer be denied that, in a globalising business environment, languages are crucial to a country’s future and must therefore also be reflected in education.
Indeed, modern languages should be regarded as ‘international communication skills’.
Private schools continue to provide young Scots with choice, diversity and excellence.
Il faut bien le faire.
John Edward is the Director of the Scottish Council of Private Schools.
